														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-674678">
									

<p>I did a good deal of research on the use of the long s for this piece. The syntactic rules varied a lot over time, and at the end of the 18th century I'm pretty sure it did appear at the beginnings of words. If someone more schooled on this topic can shed some light on it, please do so.</p>
<p>If you're interested:<br />
<a href="http://babelstone.blogspot.com/2006/06/rules-for-long-s.html">Link</a><br />
(Note "ſituation" and "the faithful ſtork")</p>
<p>Edit: I admit I wasn't completely consistent with it, because it looks really weird on three letter words like "ſix" or "ſea", or before h, as in "fiſh".</p>

